<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<speak version="1.1" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2001/10/synthesis">

<voice name="V2">
<prosody rate="95%" pitch="-2st">

The age of typing prompts into a chat window <break time="400ms"/> is ending.

<break time="800ms"/>

For two years, the world marveled at large language models. <break time="300ms"/> We asked them questions. <break time="200ms"/> We watched them write poems and debug code. <break time="200ms"/> We were impressed and sometimes alarmed.

<break time="600ms"/>

But here is what most people missed. <break time="400ms"/> Those interactions were never the destination. <break time="300ms"/> They were the warmup.

<break time="800ms"/>

The real shift is happening now. <break time="300ms"/> It is not about better prompts or smarter models. <break time="300ms"/> It is about something more consequential. <break time="400ms"/> The transition from AI as a tool you talk to, <break time="300ms"/> into AI as a system that works.

<break time="600ms"/>

Welcome to the era of <emphasis level="moderate">Agentic AI</emphasis>.

<break time="1200ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: The Limits of Single-Call Inference.

<break time="500ms"/>

Let us start by understanding what we are leaving behind.

<break time="500ms"/>

When you type a prompt into ChatGPT or Claude, you make a single call to a language model. <break time="200ms"/> You send input. <break time="200ms"/> The model generates output. <break time="200ms"/> The interaction ends. <break time="300ms"/> This is called <emphasis level="moderate">single-call inference</emphasis>.

<break time="400ms"/>

Definition: Single-call inference is a one-shot request-response pattern with no memory or iteration.

<break time="500ms"/>

It is useful. <break time="200ms"/> It is accessible. <break time="300ms"/> And for production workloads, it is fundamentally limited.

<break time="500ms"/>

Single-call systems have no memory between interactions. <break time="200ms"/> They cannot plan across multiple steps. <break time="200ms"/> They cannot use external tools. <break time="200ms"/> They cannot verify their own outputs.

<break time="400ms"/>

Failure mode: no error recovery. <break time="300ms"/> Failure mode: no context retention.

<break time="400ms"/>

In short, they respond. <break time="300ms"/> They do not work.

<break time="600ms"/>

Agentic AI is different. <break time="300ms"/> An agent is not a chatbot with extra features. <break time="200ms"/> It is a <emphasis level="moderate">system architecture</emphasis>.

<break time="400ms"/>

Definition: An agent is a pipeline that orchestrates language models with planning, memory, tool use, and safety checks.

<break time="500ms"/>

When we say agentic, we mean the AI can perceive its environment. <break time="200ms"/> It can reason about goals. <break time="200ms"/> It can take actions and observe results. <break time="200ms"/> It can iterate until done.

<break time="400ms"/>

For engineers: think of agents as stateful control loops with external tool access.

<break time="500ms"/>

This is the transition. <break time="300ms"/> From AI as interface, <break time="200ms"/> to AI as infrastructure.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: Agentic Architecture Components.

<break time="500ms"/>

What does an agentic system actually look like?

<break time="500ms"/>

At the highest level, an agent is a pipeline with five core components.

<break time="600ms"/>

First, <emphasis level="moderate">planning</emphasis>. <break time="300ms"/> The agent decomposes a goal into subtasks. <break time="200ms"/> It decides on execution order. <break time="200ms"/> It adapts when things go wrong.

<break time="400ms"/>

Constraint: planning requires structured decision-making under uncertainty.

<break time="500ms"/>

Second, tools. <break time="300ms"/> An agent without tools is just a language model with extra steps. <break time="300ms"/> Tools are interfaces to the real world. <break time="200ms"/> APIs. <break time="150ms"/> Databases. <break time="150ms"/> Code interpreters. <break time="150ms"/> Search engines.

<break time="400ms"/>

For engineers: tool integration defines what the agent can actually do.

<break time="500ms"/>

Third, <emphasis level="moderate">memory</emphasis>. <break time="300ms"/> Agents retain information across steps. <break time="200ms"/> Short-term memory holds current task context. <break time="200ms"/> Long-term memory stores knowledge across sessions.

<break time="400ms"/>

Failure mode: without memory, agents repeat mistakes indefinitely.

<break time="500ms"/>

Fourth, safety loops. <break time="300ms"/> This includes guardrails that filter harmful outputs. <break time="200ms"/> Policy checks enforce business rules. <break time="200ms"/> Evaluation layers assess alignment.

<break time="400ms"/>

Enterprise driver: compliance. <break time="300ms"/> Safety is not optional. <break time="200ms"/> It is load-bearing.

<break time="500ms"/>

Fifth, <emphasis level="moderate">human-in-the-loop</emphasis>. <break time="300ms"/> Not every decision should be automated. <break time="200ms"/> Agents must know when to pause and escalate.

<break time="400ms"/>

For product and technical leaders: HITL is how you maintain oversight without sacrificing autonomy.

<break time="600ms"/>

Here is the mental model that matters. <break time="300ms"/> Agents are pipelines, not personas. <break time="300ms"/> They are systems you deploy, not characters you chat with.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: Enterprise Adoption Drivers.

<break time="500ms"/>

Why are enterprises making this transition now?

<break time="500ms"/>

Three drivers dominate.

<break time="600ms"/>

First, reliability. <break time="300ms"/> Single-call systems are brittle. <break time="200ms"/> They hallucinate. <break time="200ms"/> They miss context. <break time="200ms"/> They cannot recover from errors.

<break time="400ms"/>

Enterprise driver: failure tolerance. <break time="300ms"/> Agentic architectures introduce checkpoints, retries, and verification.

<break time="500ms"/>

Second, <emphasis level="moderate">traceability</emphasis>. <break time="300ms"/> In regulated industries, you must know what the AI did. <break time="200ms"/> Why it did it. <break time="200ms"/> What data it used.

<break time="400ms"/>

Enterprise driver: audit trails. <break time="300ms"/> Agents log every step, every tool call, every memory access.

<break time="500ms"/>

Third, integration. <break time="300ms"/> Enterprises do not run isolated models. <break time="200ms"/> They run systems that connect to CRMs, ERPs, and internal APIs.

<break time="400ms"/>

For product and technical leaders: integration is where AI meets existing infrastructure.

<break time="600ms"/>

The result is a new category of workload. <break time="300ms"/> AI that executes workflows. <break time="200ms"/> AI that manages processes. <break time="200ms"/> AI that operates.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: Certification Alignment.

<break time="500ms"/>

This module maps to several certification domains.

<break time="500ms"/>

The certification expects you to understand the industry shift from prompting to agentic architectures. <break time="300ms"/> You must recognize the limitations of single-call inference.

<break time="500ms"/>

This aligns with NVIDIA exam domains around architectural awareness and vocabulary alignment.

<break time="400ms"/>

Terms like <emphasis level="moderate">agent loop</emphasis>, tool use, grounding, and human-in-the-loop appear throughout the exam. <break time="300ms"/> This module establishes the conceptual foundation.

<break time="500ms"/>

Think of this as the orientation layer. <break time="300ms"/> The rest of the course builds on these ideas.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="98%">

Section: Key Takeaways.

<break time="600ms"/>

Prompting was never the product. <break time="300ms"/> It was the user interface for early adoption.

<break time="500ms"/>

Agents are not chatbots. <break time="300ms"/> They are architectures combining planning, tools, memory, safety, and human oversight.

<break time="500ms"/>

Enterprises adopt agentic AI for reliability, traceability, and integration. <break time="300ms"/> These are requirements, not features.

<break time="500ms"/>

NVIDIA is formalizing this transition. <break time="300ms"/> The certification validates that you understand how agentic systems are built and operated.

<break time="600ms"/>

This is the new baseline. <break time="400ms"/> Let us build on it.

<break time="1000ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

</speak>
